sect2.para:
Research has found that women are almost twice as likely as men to receive a diagnosis of an anxiety disorder over their lifetime (Mc Lean et al.,
            2011
         ). However, there does not appear to be any gender differences in the age of onset and chronology of anxiety disorders (Mc Lean et al.,
            2011
         ). The gender difference in the prevalence of anxiety disorders is often described via the vulnerability-stress model. This biological predisposition (Lebron-Milad & Milad, 
            2012
         ) is then paired with experiences of gender-role socialization, increased reported life stress for women, and the use of emotion-focus coping to further explain the sex differences in anxiety disorders (Matud, 
            2004
         ). Additionally, there is the risk of gender bias in client reporting of symptoms in which men may be less willing to disclose feelings of anxiety due to gendered socialization which taught them that these feelings were not acceptable for men (Hallers-Haalboom et al., 
            2020
         ).

Lesbian, gay, bisexual, queer, and transgender (LGBT)
   Lesbian, gay, bisexual, queer, and transgender (LGBT)
 individuals have also been found to report higher rates of anxiety than their straight or cisgender peers (Reisner et al., 
   2016
). The minority stress model theorizes that this increased risk is due to additional environmental stress resulting from factors like discrimination, stigma, and structural inequity due to heteronormativity leading to higher rates of anxiety (Meyer, 
   2003
). Transgender youth have also been found to report significantly higher rates of GAD compared to their cisgender peers (Chodzen et al., 
   2019
). This relationship is believed to be particularly strong for transgender youth who reported thoughts of internalized transphobia. Clinicians should be cognizant of the increased risk of anxiety disorders for women and LGBT individuals and the potential predisposition for underreporting of symptoms in men when considering a diagnosis.

Anxiety disorders are generally found to be less common for older adults compared to younger adults (Wolitzky-Taylor et al.,
            2010
         ). However, despite this overall decrease in prevalence as a function of age, anxiety disorders are still one of the most diagnosed disorders in older individuals. Assessment for anxiety disorders is often more difficult than for younger adults due to differences in how older adults describe anxiety, higher rates of medical comorbidities that complicate or mask diagnosis, and cognitive changes due to age-related decline (Balsamo et al., 
            2018
         ). Older adults are less likely to discuss their negative emotions or select absolute descriptors like “never” and “always” when completing self-report measures (Balsamo et al., 
            2018
         ). Additionally, compared to younger adults, older adults are more likely to report feelings of shame and guilt related to anxiety disorder rather than feelings of fear. Due to these known differences in the presentation of anxiety disorder in older adults, specific self-report measures have been developed to assess anxiety in this population. The Geriatric Anxiety Inventory (Pachana et al., 
            2007
         ), Geriatric Anxiety Scale (Segal et al., 
            2010
         ), and Worry Scale (Wisocki et al., 
            1986
         ) are well-supported self-report measures for assessing anxiety symptoms in older adults.

Previous research has found that White Americans were significantly more likely to meet diagnostic criteria for anxiety disorders compared to Black Americans, Hispanic Americans, and Asian Americans (Asnaani et al.,
            2010
         ). This finding was found even when controlling for the age, gender, and socioeconomic status of the participants. In the same study, Asian Americans were the least likely to report an anxiety disorder. Additionally, individuals who immigrated to the United States were found to have lower rates of GAD than those born in the United States (Budhwani et al., 
            2015
         ). However, the study also found that experiences of racial or ethnic discrimination were significantly associated with an increased risk of GAD. The increased stress experienced by racial or ethnic minority individuals in the United States from experiences of discrimination and transgenerational passing of stress is hypothesized to increase the risk that an individual will develop an anxiety disorder (Thoits, 
            2010
         ). Additionally, the differences between diagnosis rates of anxiety disorders may be due to lower utilization of mental healthcare services by Black and Hispanic individuals compared to White individuals in the United States (De Luca et al., 
            2016
         ).

Some descriptions of anxiety are culturally bound. In the Culture and Psychiatric Diagnosis section of the DSM-5-TR, there are examples of some of these culturally based concepts for describing or understanding distress which clients may reference (APA, 
            2022
         ). For instance, nervios is a term used in many Latinx communities to describe a range of symptoms including headaches, nervousness, gastrointestinal disturbance, emotional distress, and inability to complete tasks (APA, 
            2022
         ). Additionally, the DSM-5-TR identifies some culture-bound disorders that share some similarities to the disorders described in the anxiety section of the book. A diagnosis of taijin kyofusho may be more descriptive than social anxiety disorder for an individual from Japan who expresses anxiety around social interactions due to a fear that their appearance or odor will offend others.

Low socioeconomic status (SES) has been shown to be associated with high rates of anxiety disorders and poorer treatment outcomes (Nunes et al.,
            2022
         ). Additionally, low neighborhood income and high crime rates were also associated with elevated levels of general anxiety (Finegan et al., 
            2020
         ). Longitudinal research suggests that both growing up in poverty and experiencing life events that result
            result
          in increased financial hardship are predictors for developing a variety of negative mental health outcomes including increased anxiety (Ridley et al., 
            2020
         ). Furthermore, socioeconomic disparities often function to sustain anxiety disorder through financial barriers to treatments, increased worry about finances, and potentially higher rates of exposure to crime near the home (Ridley et al., 
            2020
         ).
